{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-05908/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-05908"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:59:08"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, pan, tracking"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["three shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman helps a seamstress."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-05908","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-05908"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1/d2822ed4-7ebd-411f-ad1d-c2a40bd73c7b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T15:35:13.256Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>This shot shows a high society woman from the Princess’ posse, a seamstress, and Alma triangulated to show different stages of social hierarchy. A seamstress provides the service to a noble-adjacent woman, while Alma is in the middle, elevated in the frame yet lower in the social rungs. Alma’s slow transformation recalls George Bernard Shaw’s play <em>Pygmalion</em>, in which phonetician Henry Higgings accepts a bet that he can turn working-class flower girl Eliza into a culture woman that can pass as royalty. As an experiment, Eliza ends the play in the middle, not quite belonging to high society nor her original social circle. Like Eliza, Alma here is in between, trying to find her place in the house of Woodcock and among its high society world, though she is closer to the workers than the noblewomen. Shaw’s play is based on the <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW263084225 BCX0\" href=\"https://ptannotated.com/items/phan-03435.html\"><u>myth of Pygmalion</u></a> and served as the basis for the 1964 musical film <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW263084225 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0058385/\"><em><u>My Fair Lady</u></em></a>.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05908/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:25.802748909339712,25.71364927445508,299.9641628440367,251.2543004587157"}}}]}]}]}